===Etymology 3===
French ''[[déserter]]'', from late Latin ''[[desertare]]'', from Latin ''[[desertus]]'', from ''[[deserere]]'' ‘abandon’.

====Pronunciation====
*{{IPA|/dɪ'zɜ:t/}}
*{{AHD|dĭzû(r)t'}}, {{SAMPA|/dI"z3:(r)t/}}
*{{audio|en-us-desert-verb.ogg|Audio (US), verb}}

=====Homophones=====
*[[dessert]]

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# To leave ([[anything]] that [[depend]]s on one's [[presence]] to [[survive]], [[exist]], or [[succeed]]), especially when contrary to a [[promise]] or [[obligation]]; to [[abandon]]; to [[forsake]].
#:''You can't just drive off and '''desert''' me here, in the middle of nowhere.''
# To [[leave]] one's duty or post, especially to leave a [[military]] or [[naval]] [[unit]] without permission
#:''Anyone found '''deserting''' will be shot.''

=====Derived terms=====
*[[deserter]]
*[[desertion]]
*[[desert or leave a sinking ship]]

